{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492709"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:42:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:42:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1136"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1136"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.1,0.35,0.04,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1136"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105700"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1136","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1136"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1136"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88166"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"647"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12911"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6286"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7346"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44500"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105700","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105700"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents with a one day history of colicky lower abdominal pain associated with vomiting. The pain has now shifted to the right iliac fossa and is constant. She migrated to Australia from Afghanistan 35 years ago. She speaks limited English and with the aid of a telephone interpreter service it is not possible to gather a clear history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.2\u00baC. Her abdomen is slightly distended and there is some tenderness in the right lower quadrant. A plain abdominal radiograph is performed. (Image 1, 2)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the calcification?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Faecolith","Gallstone","Ureteric calculus","Hydatid disease","Tuberculosis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis X-ray shows an isolated, calcified structure in the pelvis. Given that this patient has migrated from an area of the world where \u003Cstrong\u003Etuberculosis (TB)\u003C/strong\u003E is endemic, nodal calcification following active infection is a reasonable differential. However, her current symptoms do not fit with this diagnosis, and on further inspection of the structure itself, it only has a calcified rim which is inconsistent with the appearance of a calcified lymph node, making TB less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHydatid disease\u003C/strong\u003E is an endemic parasitic condition throughout much of Asia and Europe caused by \u003Cem\u003EEnchinococcus granulosas\u003C/em\u003E. In Australia, hydatid disease is generally confined to sheep graziers. While they do calcify peripherally, hydatid cysts most commonly affect the liver. As the structure displayed is not within the right upper quadrant, it is unlikely to be hydatid disease. Similarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Egallstones\u003C/strong\u003E would generally be seen in the right upper quadrant and are diagnosed more commonly by ultrasound due to increased sensitivity. \u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUreteric calculi\u003C/strong\u003E can be seen anywhere along the length of the ureter, and therefore may be present within the right iliac fossa. While the pain of a renal stone is also described as \u2018colicky,\u2019 it radiates in the typical \u2018loin to groin\u2019 pattern, which is absent in this case. As with gallstones, not all ureteric stones can be seen on plain X-ray, and CT is preferred.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHardened faeces, a \u003Cstrong\u003Efaecolith \u003C/strong\u003Ecan occur anywhere within the intestines, but typically within the colon. They can be seen on plain X-ray (Image) and, when present in the appendix (appendicolith), are present within the right iliac fossa. While they are often an incidental finding, this patient\u0027s symptoms now suggest that she has developed appendicitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The location and appearance of abdominal calcifications \u2013 alongside history and examination, is useful to confirm a diagnosis."],"references":["Zulfiqar M, Shetty A, Tsai R, Gagnon MH, Balfe DM, Mellnick VM. Diagnostic approach to benign and malignant calcifications in the abdomen and pelvis. Radiographics 2020 Aug;40(3): 731-53. https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020190152"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88166"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1136"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17780"},{"type":"media","id":"17781"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21052"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17780"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/763786de-1913-432d-80a9-4c27c7afeaab.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/stor